: OrchidsExtant Campanian first appearancesHidden categories: Webarchive template wayback linksCS1 Spanish-language sources (es)Articles with short descriptionShort description is different from WikidataUse dmy dates from October 2021Articles with \'species\' microformatsArticles containing Ancient Greek (to 1453)-language textAll articles with unsourced statementsArticles with unsourced statements from April 2014Commons category link from WikidataPages using eFloras template without author namesPages using eFloras template without volumeTaxonbars with 30–34 taxon IDsArticles with BNF identifiersArticles with BNFdata identifiersArticles with GND identifiersArticles with J9U identifiersArticles with LCCN identifiersArticles with NDL identifiersArticles with NKC identifiers\n\n\n\n\n\n\n This page was last edited on 12 May 2024, at 03:40 (UTC).\nText is available under the Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike License 4.0;\nadditional terms may apply. By using this site, you agree to the Terms of Use and Privacy Policy. Wikipedia® is a registered trademark of the Wikimedia Foundation, Inc., a non-profit organization.\n\n\nPrivacy policy\nAbout Wikipedia\nDisclaimers\nContact Wikipedia\nCode of Conduct\nDevelopers\nStatistics\nCookie statement\nMobile view\nEdit preview settings\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nToggle limited content width\n\n\n\n\n\n\n',3),(19,'Pavia - Wikipedia','C:\\Users\\daniy\\OneDrive\\Desktop\\Digital_Content_Retrieval\\level1\\level2\\level3\\level4\\Pavia - Wikipedia.html','.html',1293782,'\nPavia - Wikipedia\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n                        Donate your 5×1000 to Wikimedia Italia. Text 94039910156.\n                    \n\n\n\n\nFind out more\n\n\n            Close\n            \n\n\n[ hide ]Take part in the two events currently underway: Take part in the Festival of sources and the writing week on museums ! \n\n\nPavia\n\nFrom Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.\n\n\n\nGo to navigation\nGo to search\n\n\n\n Disambiguation – If you are looking for other meanings, see Pavia (disambiguation) .\n\nPavia municipality\n\n\n\nPavia – View\nLocationState Italy\nRegion Lombardy\nProvince Pavia\nAdministrationMayorFabrizio Fracassi ( LSP ) since 5-30-2019\nTerritoryCoordinates45°11′07.01″N  9°09′18″E﻿ / ﻿45.185281°N 9.155°E45.185281; 9,155﻿ ( Pavia )Coordinates : 45°11′07.01″N  9°09′18″E﻿ / ﻿45.185281°N 9.155°E45.185281; 9,155﻿ ( Pavia ) ( Map )\nAltitude77  m  above sea level\nSurface62.86 km²\nInhabitants71 371 [1]  (28-2-2024)\nDensity1 135.4 inhabitants /km²\nFractionsSee list\nNeighboring municipalitiesBorgarello , Carbonara al Ticino , Certosa di Pavia , Cura Carpignano , Marcignago , San Genesio ed Uniti , San Martino Siccomario , Sant\'Alessio con Vialone , Torre d\'Isola , Travacò Siccomario , Valle Salimbene\nMore informationPostal code27100\nPrefix0382\nJet lagUTC+1\nISTAT code018110\nLand registry codeG388\nPlatePV\nCl. seismiczone 3 (low seismicity) [2]\nCl. climatezone E, 2,623 days [3]\nName of inhabitantspavia\nPatronSan Siro , Sant\'Agostino , San Teodoro\nHolidayDecember 9th and August 28th\nNicknameSecond Rome City of a hundred towers\nCartographyPavia\nPavia – MapLocation of the municipality of Pavia in the province of the same name\nInstitutional siteEdit data on Wikidata  ·  Manual\nPavia ( IPA : /paˈviːa/ [4] ,pronounceⓘ ;[pɐˈviːɐ]inPavia dialect) is anItalian municipalityof 71,371 inhabitants[1],capitalof theprovince of the same nameinLombardy.\nLocated along the Via Francigena [5] , the Via Francisca and on the banks of the Ticino river , just north of the latter\'s confluence with the Po , the city traces its origins to the time of the Gallic tribes  ; it subsequently became a Roman municipium with the name of Ticinum . In the Middle Ages it was (together with Ravenna and Verona ) one of the royal seats of the Ostrogothic Kingdom , it was the capital of the Lombard Kingdom for two centuries and then, from 774 to 1024 [6] , capital of the Italian Kingdom , while from 1365 to 1413 it hosted the court viscontia ; since 1361 it has been home to a renowned university , recognized by the Times Higher Education in 2022 among the top 10 in Italy and among the 300 best in the world, out of a sample of 2,112 university institutes examined [7] .\n The ancient origins and an important historical past have left Pavia with a notable artistic heritage: among the main tourist attractions of the city, counted among the cities of art of the Po Valley, we can mention the Visconteo Castle , the basilica of San Michele Maggiore , the basilica of San Pietro in Ciel d\'Oro , the church of Santa Maria del Carmine , the Duomo , the Romanesque towers , the Civic Museums and the Covered Bridge . The city is also the capital of a province dedicated above all to agriculture , in particular viticulture , rice cultivation and cereal cultivation , while the weight of the industrial sector, once very significant, is today much more limited. Pavia is included in the Ticino park and within the municipal borders there are some woods ( Bosco Negri and Bosco Grande [8] ) which are witnesses of the large lowland forest that once covered the Po Valley .\n\nIndex\n\n1 Physical geography\n\n1.1 Territory\n1.2 Climate\n\n\n2 Etymology\n3 History\n\n3.1 Roman times\n3.2 Medieval era\n3.3 Modern era\n3.4 Contemporary era\n3.5 Symbols\n3.6 Honors\n\n\n4 Monuments and places of interest\n\n4.1 Religious architecture\n\n4.1.1 Basilica of San Michele Maggiore\n4.1.2 Pavia Cathedral\n4.1.3 Basilica of San Pietro in Ciel d\'Oro\n4.1.4 Church of Santa Maria del Carmine\n4.1.5 Church of San Teodoro\n4.1.6 Chiesa di Santa Maria di Canepanova\n4.1.7 Altre chiese\n4.1.8 Chiese inglobate in edifici residenziali o adattate ad altri usi\n4.1.9 Chiese andate distrutte\n\n\n4.2 Architetture civili\n\n4.2.1 Il Palazzo Regio\n4.2.2 Ponte Coperto\n4.2.3 Palazzi\n4.2.4 Broletto\n\n\n4.3 Architetture militari\n\n4.3.1 Le torri\